[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] There's another broker under the ActiveMQ umbrella code-named *Artemis*.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] The ActiveMQ project was originally created by its founders from LogicBlaze in 2004, as an open source message broker, hosted by CodeHaus.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] The code and ActiveMQ trademark were donated to the Apache Software Foundation in 2007, where the founders continued to develop the codebase with the extended Apache community.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Artemis is another broker under the ActiveMQ umbrella based on the HornetQ code-base which was donated from the JBoss community to the Apache ActiveMQ community in 2015.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Artemis is the "next generation" broker from ActiveMQ.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Artemis is a multi-protocol, embeddable, high performance, clustered, asynchronous messaging system.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] ActiveMQ Classic uses several modes for high availability, including both file-system and database row-level locking mechanisms, sharing of the persistence store via a shared filesystem, or true replication using Apache ZooKeeper.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] ActiveMQ supports a horizontal scaling mechanism called a Network of Brokers out of the box.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] ActiveMQ supports a number of transport protocols, including OpenWire, STOMP, MQTT, AMQP, REST, and WebSockets.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] ActiveMQ is used in enterprise service bus implementations such as Apache ServiceMix and Mule.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Other projects using ActiveMQ include Apache Camel and Apache CXF in SOA infrastructure projects.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Coinciding with the release of Apache ActiveMQ 5.3, the world's first results for the SPECjms2007 industry standard benchmark were announced.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Four results were submitted to the SPEC and accepted for publication.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] The results cover different topologies to analyze the scalability of Apache ActiveMQ in two dimensions.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Apache is used in enterprise software and offers limited ActiveMQ support on a voluntary basis.
[src:stomp-protocol/apache-activemq] Users that need more extensive support may need to consult commercial companies specializing in ActiveMQ.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM allows application modules to be distributed over heterogeneous platforms and reduces the complexity of developing applications that span multiple operating systems and network protocols.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The middleware creates a distributed communications layer that insulates the application developer from the details of the various operating systems and network interfaces.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Application programming interfaces (APIs) that extend across diverse platforms and networks are typically provided by MOM.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] This middleware layer allows software components (applications, servlets, and other components) that have been developed independently and might run on different networked platforms to interact with one another.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Applications distributed on different network nodes use the application interface to communicate.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, by providing an administrative interface, this new, virtual system of interconnected applications can be made fault tolerant and secure.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM provides software elements that reside in all communicating components of a client/server architecture and typically support asynchronous calls between the client and server applications.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM reduces the involvement of application developers with the complexity of the master-slave nature of the client/server mechanism.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] All these models make it possible for one software component to affect the behavior of another component over a network.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] They are different in that RPC- and ORB-based middleware create systems of tightly coupled components, whereas MOM-based systems allow for a loose coupling of components.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In an RPC- or ORB-based system, when one procedure calls another, it must wait for the called procedure to return before it can do anything else.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In these mostly synchronous messaging models, the middleware functions partly as a super-linker, locating the called procedure on a network and using network services to pass function or method parameters to the procedure and then to return results.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Note that Object request brokers also support fully asynchronous messaging via oneway invocations.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Central reasons for using a message-based communications protocol include its ability to store (buffer), route, or transform messages while conveying them from senders to receivers.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Another advantage of messaging provider-mediated messaging between clients is that by adding an administrative interface, you can monitor and tune performance.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Client applications are thus effectively relieved of every problem except that of sending, receiving, and processing messages.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It is up to the code that implements the MOM system and up to the administrator to resolve issues like interoperability, reliability, security, scalability, and performance.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Using a MOM system, a client makes an API call to send a message to a destination managed by the provider.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The call invokes provider services to route and deliver the message.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Once it has sent the message, the client can continue to do other work, confident that the provider retains the message until a receiving client retrieves it.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The message-based model, coupled with the mediation of the provider, makes it possible to create a system of loosely coupled components.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM comprises a category of inter-application communication software that generally relies on asynchronous message-passing, as opposed to a request-response architecture.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In asynchronous systems, message queues provide temporary storage when the destination program is busy or not connected.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, most asynchronous MOM systems provide persistent storage to back up the message queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] This means that the sender and receiver do not need to connect to the network at the same time (asynchronous delivery), and problems with intermittent connectivity are solved.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It also means that should the receiver application fail for any reason, the senders can continue unaffected, as the messages they send will simply accumulate in the message queue for later processing when the receiver restarts.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Many message-oriented middleware implementations depend on a message queue system.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations permit routing logic to be provided by the messaging layer itself, while others depend on client applications to provide routing information or allow for a mix of both paradigms.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations make use of broadcast or multicast distribution paradigms.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In a message-based middleware system, the message received at the destination need not be identical to the message originally sent.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A MOM system with built-in intelligence can transform messages and route to match the requirements of the sender or of the recipient.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In conjunction with the routing and broadcast/multicast facilities, one application can send a message in its own native format, and two or more other applications may each receive a copy of the message in their own native format.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Many modern MOM systems provide sophisticated message transformation (or mapping) tools which allow programmers to specify transformation rules applicable to a simple GUI drag-and-drop operation.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The primary disadvantage of many message-oriented middleware systems is that they require an extra component in the architecture, the message transfer agent (message broker).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] As with any system, adding another component can lead to reductions in performance and reliability, and can also make the system as a whole more difficult and expensive to maintain.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, many inter-application communications have an intrinsically synchronous aspect, with the sender specifically wanting to wait for a reply to a message before continuing (see real-time computing and near-real-time for extreme cases).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Because message-based communication inherently functions asynchronously, it may not fit well in such situations.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] That said, most MOM systems have facilities to group a request and a response as a single pseudo-synchronous transaction.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] With a synchronous messaging system, the calling function does not return until the called function has finished its task.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In a loosely coupled asynchronous system, the calling client can continue to load work upon the recipient until the resources needed to handle this work are depleted and the called component fails.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Of course, these conditions can be minimized or avoided by monitoring performance and adjusting message flow, but this is work that is not needed with a synchronous messaging system.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The important thing is to understand the advantages and liabilities of each kind of system.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Each system is appropriate for different kinds of tasks.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Sometimes, a combination of the two kinds of systems is required to obtain the desired behavior.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Historically, there was a lack of standards governing the use of message-oriented middleware that has caused problems.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Most of the major vendors have their own implementations, each with its own application programming interface (API) and management tools.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] One of the long-standing standards for message-oriented middleware is X/Open group's XATMI specification (Distributed Transaction Processing: The XATMI Specification) which standardizes API for interprocess communications.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Known implementations for this API is ATR Baltic's Enduro/X middleware and Oracle's Tuxedo.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an approved OASIS and ISO standard that defines the protocol and formats used between participating application components, so implementations are interoperable.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It also supports transaction management, queuing, distribution, security, management, clustering, federation and heterogeneous multi-platform support.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Java applications that use AMQP are typically written in Java JMS.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Other implementations provide APIs for C#, C++, PHP, Python, Ruby, and other programming languages.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The High Level Architecture (HLA IEEE 1516) is an Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) standard for simulation interoperability.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It defines a set of services, provided through an API in C++ or Java.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The services offer publish/subscribe-based information exchange, based on a modular Federation Object Model.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] There are also services for coordinated data exchange and time advance, based on logical simulation time, as well as synchronization points.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Additional services provide transfer of ownership, data distribution optimizations and monitoring and management of participating Federates (systems).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The MQ Telemetry Transport (MQTT) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922) supported by the OASIS organization.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It provides a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol on top of TCP/IP suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts where a small code footprint is required and/or network bandwidth is at a premium.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Object Management Group's Data Distribution Service (DDS) provides message-oriented Publish/Subscribe (P/S) middleware standard that aims to enable scalable, real-time, dependable, high-performance and interoperable data exchanges between publishers and subscribers.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The standard provides interfaces to C++, C++11, C, Ada, Java, and Ruby.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The eXtensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a communications protocol for message-oriented middleware based on Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Designed to be extensible, the protocol has also been used for publish-subscribe systems, signalling for VoIP, video, file transfer, gaming, Internet of Things applications such as the smart grid, and social networking services.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Unlike most instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard and uses an open systems approach of development and application, by which anyone may implement an XMPP service and interoperate with other organizations' implementations.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Because XMPP is an open protocol, implementations can be developed using any software license; although many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software, many freeware and proprietary software implementations also exist.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The XMPP Working group produced four specifications (RFC 3920, RFC 3921, RFC 3922, RFC 3923), which were approved as Proposed Standards in 2004.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] XMPP-based software is deployed widely across the Internet, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation, and forms the basis for the Department of Defense (DoD) Unified Capabilities Framework.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A similar effort is with the actively evolving OpenMAMA project, which aims to provide a common API, especially to C clients.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] As of August 2012, it is mainly appropriate for distributing market-oriented data (e.g. stock quotes) over pub-sub middleware.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Message queues allow the exchange of information between distributed applications.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A message queue can reside in memory or disk storage.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Messages stay in the queue until the time they are processed by a service consumer.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Through the message queue, the application can be implemented independently - they do not need to know each other's position, or continue to implement procedures to remove the need for waiting to receive this message.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:stomp-protocol/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:stomp-protocol/streaming-text-oriented-messaging-protocol] Communication between client and server is through a "frame" consisting of a number of lines.
[src:stomp-protocol/streaming-text-oriented-messaging-protocol] The first line contains the command, followed by headers in the form <key>: <value> (one per line), followed by a blank line and then the body content, ending in a null character.
[src:stomp-protocol/streaming-text-oriented-messaging-protocol] Communication between server and client is through a MESSAGE, RECEIPT or ERROR frame with a similar format of headers and body content.
[src:stomp-protocol/streaming-text-oriented-messaging-protocol] Here ^@ is the caret notation for the null character.
[src:stomp-protocol/streaming-text-oriented-messaging-protocol] Lines are terminated with LF (\n, ^J, 0x10).
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] In computer networking, a **wire protocol** refers to a way of getting data from point to point: A wire protocol is needed if more than one application has to interoperate.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] It generally refers to communication protocols higher than the physical layer.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] In contrast to transport protocols at the transport level (like TCP or UDP), the term *wire protocol* is used to describe a common way to exchange information at the application level.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] It refers to an application layer protocol and defines all the required attributes for the data exchange, like data types (units of data, message formats, etc.), communication endpoints and capabilities (such as delivery guarantees, direction of communication, etc.).
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] Usually, the data is represented at the application level as a common infoset (e.g.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] XML, JSON, YAML) and requires a mechanism of data binding (using e.g. a common encoding scheme like XSD).
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] The wire protocol may be either text-based or a binary protocol.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] Although an important architectural decision, this is a separate matter from the distinction between wire protocols and programmatic APIs.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] In electronics, a wire protocol is the mechanism used to transmit data from one point to another.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] A wire protocol provides the means for the interoperation of one or more applications in a network.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] They often refer to distributed object protocols, or they use applications that were designed to work together.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] As the name suggests, these distributed object protocols run in different processes in one or several computers that are connected over a network.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] Wire protocols provide the means for a program running under one operating system to communicate with a program running under some other operating system over a network such as an organization's intranet or the Internet.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] The protocol thus interconnects multiple platforms.
[src:stomp-protocol/wire-protocol] Some wire protocols are language-independent, allowing the communication of programs written in different programming languages.
